[Student "S"]
{The bidding has been as shown.  

You <b>MIGHT</b> jump to 2NT to "show your points". However, a notrump bid now would deny a 4-card \S suit. Instead, your priority is to show that Major, so you respond 1\S. Partner bids 2\S. What do you say next? 

Partner would not support a response which might be 4 cards unless he had 4 himself. Knowing that you have two opening hands facing each other, each containing 4 \Ss, you bid the \S game.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "3"]
[Dealer "E"]
[Vulnerable "EW"]
[Deal "E:AT975.KQ.KT5.AJ7 J32.T83.43.KQT52 KQ86.J76.QJ76.96 4.A9542.A982.843"]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "4S"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "E"]
1S pass 2S pass 3S pass 4S pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 3, chOption: E, chBasis: N, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 0, nRot: 1, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "4d494a12fa3c81ea404b72ade86c8a83b9d1abe446b70e9bc94504e6cc4e4b46"]
[Category "Basic Bidding"]
[Difficulty "beginner"]
[SkillPath "basic_bidding/major_suit_openings"]
[Student "S"]
{The bidding has been as shown.  

With 4-card support you respond 2\S. Partner raises to 3\S. What do you say next? 

Partner's bid is an invitation. You have told him you have 6-10 points and he probably has about 17-18. If you are at the high end of your 6-10 he wants you to bid game, at the low end he wants you to pass. You actually have 10, definitely high end, so you bid 4\S.}

